%
When I went to law school ... I was part, virtually the last generation of American law students and
business students taught that corporations had a responsibility, because they had special priveleges
under the law, like limited liability, to their stakeholders, to their shareholders, their
employees, their customers, and the communities of which they were a part.  The, starting in the
late seventies, that practice changed, and all of a sudden the stakeholders were way up, the
shareholders were way up here, and the stakeholders were down here.  It had the ironic consequence
of giving the most influence over corporate decisions to the stakeholders with the least concern
about the long-term profitability of the corporation, and the greatest concern about the short-term
profitability.  Which accelerated a lot of these trends.

	-- Bill Clinton, _The Daily Show_, 2011
